          "title": "The Lord stood with me — the chapter's theological anchor",
          "body": "Verses 16-17 contain the chapter's deepest confession. At the first defense (likely the *prima actio* of his Roman trial), *no one supported me, but all deserted me* — the same verb (*egkatelipon*) used of Demas in v. 10. The desertion was complete. Yet *the Lord stood with me* (*ho de Kyrios moi parestē*) *and strengthened me*. The verb *paristēmi* is the same Septuagint verb used of angelic ministers standing before God; here it is Christ Himself standing beside the abandoned apostle. Two purposes are named: that *the proclamation might be fully accomplished* (*plērophorēthē*, the same verb commanded of Timothy in v. 5), and that *all the Gentiles might hear*. Even Paul's trial is missiological. The *kerygma* reached the Roman court because the Lord stood by His herald. The chapter's theology is: human desertion does not falsify divine faithfulness; the Lord's standing-by makes the herald's standing-firm possible."
